result.execSummary:
The defendant James E. Rackow was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Attempt (Felony/Battery/Theft) 3rd Degree Sexual Assault [Modifiers: Penalties for Felonies-Class "G" Felony], a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 940.225(3).
  • Criminal Trespass to Dwelling [Modifiers: Penalties for Misdemeanors-Class "A"], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.14.
  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Penalties for Misdemeanors-Class "B"], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

James E. Rackow, defendant appeared in Court in person with counsel Jonas Bednarek. Gary L. Luhman appeared as prosecuting attorney. Jury trial is still planned to go. Mr Bednarek addresses the Court regarding motions in limine of other DNA profiles found during testing. Mr Luhman responds to Mr Bednarek's motion regarding the DNA. Court reserves ruling on this motion after looking into the cases given in court as examples. Mr Bednarek's next issue raised is precluding Mr Rackow's right to question the Victim's marital status. Court rules that it will allow that question. Mr Bednarek is motioning for a right to question the Victim's demeanor and actions towards the Defendant preceding the charge. Court will allow questions regarding the Victim's marital status and the Victim's actions on the night of the alleged assault. Debra Donovan, SANE nurse is sworn in and testifies. Ms Donovan is questioned regarding her training as a SANE nurse and has treated approximately 1,000 patients. Ms Donovan informs the Court that she has testified in about 50 cases. Mr Luhman will draft the Order from today's hearing.  Hearing scheduled for November 30, 2015 at 04:00 pm.
